    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1118383866" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1118383866" />
    <a title="Clelia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11664140-clelia"><img alt="Clelia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610069682p2/11664140.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1118383866?book_show_action=true">Nov 29, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Clelia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Clelia" href="/user/show/11664140-clelia">Clelia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1118383866" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14079958190426458255">[3.5 stars]<br/><br/>I really, really tried to like this book. House of Leaves meets American Psycho meets Dean Corll meets Charles Manson meets Dennis Nilsen... it sounded directly up my alley and is an ambitious concept. But large sections really bored me, that special kind of boredom where you&apos;re afraid to admit that you&apos;re bored because it might mean that you&apos;re not intelligent or avant-garde enough to &quot;get it.&quot; So here, I&apos;m admitting it -- I was bored. The whole poetic insanity stream-of-consciousnes</span>
  <span id="freeText14079958190426458255" style="display:none">[3.5 stars]<br /><br />I really, really tried to like this book. House of Leaves meets American Psycho meets Dean Corll meets Charles Manson meets Dennis Nilsen... it sounded directly up my alley and is an ambitious concept. But large sections really bored me, that special kind of boredom where you're afraid to admit that you're bored because it might mean that you're not intelligent or avant-garde enough to "get it." So here, I'm admitting it -- I was bored. The whole poetic insanity stream-of-consciousness thing ends up seeming just like an excuse for bad editing. If this book was half its length, it could be really beautiful and arresting. There were parts of it that I lingered over, relishing the language and fantastically twisted imagery, but those only came rarely. <br /><br />Blake Butler seems very preoccupied with America and Americanness (further evidence: he often writes grimly ironic, deconstructionist reviews of fast food for Vice), and offers this book as a symbolic gesture of killing every person in America -- all 300,000,000 of them. There is one point where one of the characters\voices\malevolent spirits says, "God would you please shut the fuck up about America." But it's the sections dealing with what he sees as the Americanness of destruction and psychopathy that I found the most interesting. I also love reading about murder, and some of the scenes were genuinely terrifying (whenever he addresses the reader directly, you get a slight chill.) But again, moments like these are few and far between. For the majority of the book, Butler attempts to break down language itself by disregarding grammar and attempting Surrealist free-association for such long periods of time that your brain just switches off and stops attempting to make sense of it. The book loses its urgency in these moments. <br /><br />I feel bad for writing a bad review of this; it's a massively ambitious artistic undertaking which took Butler four years to complete. But the result is not as interesting as he seems to want it to be. The next book I read needs to be something that sticks to grammar just to detox from the long slog I took through this -- I'm thinking maybe F. Scott Fitzgerald. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14079958190426458255" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

